31:55.456 --> 31:58.243
it’s even more exciting
when he shoots someone
with it.

31:58.334 --> 31:59.870
- Bones.
- Well, it is, Booth.

31:59.960 --> 32:02.372
- And impressive.
He never misses.
- Andy sometimes misses.

32:02.463 --> 32:04.749
- Yes. See?
- Sorry about that, pal.

32:04.840 --> 32:06.831
I get it.
Cop’s gotta be careful.

32:06.926 --> 32:08.666
See that box of ammo
right there?

32:16.811 --> 32:18.802
Aha!

32:18.896 --> 32:22.059
- Gotcha, dirtbag!
- Got me for what?

32:22.149 --> 32:24.310
Don’t write that.
Don’t write “dirtbag.”

32:26.278 --> 32:28.394
What? Got him.

32:33.327 --> 32:36.069
Officer Grant says
you have quite a temper.

32:36.163 --> 32:38.996
Yeah. Well, guy starts
writing love letters
to your girlfriend,

32:39.083 --> 32:40.994
then she dumps you for him?

32:41.085 --> 32:43.121
He’s gonna get
a pop in the nose.
It’s practically the law, right?

32:43.212 --> 32:45.077
Yeah. Right.
So, you punch him
in the nose.

32:45.214 --> 32:46.704
That’s fine.
Thank you.

32:46.799 --> 32:49.165
Then you find out
that it wasn’t Colin Casey
who wrote the letters.

32:49.260 --> 32:50.921
What? He admitted it.

32:51.011 --> 32:53.297
No. No, no, no.
He hired someone else
to write the letters.

32:53.389 --> 32:55.926
You find that out, then
you get really pissed off
and you shoot him.

32:56.016 --> 32:58.598
- Who?
- Martin Aragon. The guy who
actually wrote the letters.

32:58.686 --> 33:01.143
Whoa. Wait, wait.
So she dumped me
for another guy?

33:01.272 --> 33:03.388
No, she dumps you for Colin.
All right, now I’m confused.

33:03.482 --> 33:06.440
The point of all this
is that we have
your fancy blue bullets...

33:06.527 --> 33:08.313
and the gun,
and we know where
you shot him.

33:08.404 --> 33:11.396
I never shot my gun.
I told you already.

33:11.490 --> 33:13.697
Okay? I might
wave it around
from time to time...

33:13.784 --> 33:16.821
if some bad-lookin’ dude
comes in myjoint,
but I never shot it.

33:16.912 --> 33:18.868
And plus, I’m sure
you figured out...

33:18.956 --> 33:20.912
that those blue bullets
don’t fit in that gun.

33:21.000 --> 33:24.288
- Guy could have two guns.
- Who are you sayin’
I killed again?

33:24.378 --> 33:26.960
If you have nothin’ to hide,
why don’t you just
show me the gun...

33:27.047 --> 33:29.129
that uses
these fancy blue bullets.

33:31.218 --> 33:33.129
Okay, let the record show
that the suspect acted...

33:33.220 --> 33:35.302
very suspiciously
when | asked him
to produce the weapon.

33:35.389 --> 33:38.597
No. Wait. Okay.

33:39.894 --> 33:42.601
- I gave the gun to somebody.
- Who?

33:42.688 --> 33:45.179
She said I was
a stiff sometimes.
All right?

33:45.274 --> 33:49.267
Bonng,lguess.
She wanted me
to be a little romantic.

33:49.361 --> 33:52.853
So I gave her the gun
that brought us together
in the first place.

33:52.948 --> 33:55.155
Officer Grant?
Yeah.

33:55.242 --> 33:57.904
Got it engra veo’,
and / gave it to her
for Valentine ’3 Day.

33:57.995 --> 34:01.283
So now are you gonna inform the record
on what to show on that?

34:01.373 --> 34:03.284
There’s nobody in there.

34:06.795 --> 34:08.786
Here you go.
Officer Grant,
thanks for coming in.

34:08.881 --> 34:11.588
Can I have
your sidearm, please?

34:11.675 --> 34:13.586
What’s this about?

34:13.677 --> 34:16.464
Well, we got a warrant
to, uh, search your apartment.

34:18.057 --> 34:19.968
Have a seat, please.

34:21.310 --> 34:24.052
We, uh, found Eddie’s gun.

34:24.146 --> 34:28.640
Says, “You can
arrest me anytime. Eddie. ”

34:29.693 --> 34:31.809
You’re a law-enforcement
professional.

34:31.904 --> 34:34.441
Why would you keep
the murder weapon?

34:34.531 --> 34:36.237
I am a law enforcement
professional,

34:36.325 --> 34:39.658
and if you had any evidence
that wasn’t circumstantial,
you’d have arrested me.

34:39.745 --> 34:43.237
So I guess I’ll be leaving.
It’s been a pleasure.

34:43.332 --> 34:45.618
Uh, hold on
for one second, please.

34:47.294 --> 34:49.159
We also have a warrant
for your shoes.

34:49.255 --> 34:51.496
My shoes?

34:54.718 --> 34:56.379
What’s that?

34:56.470 --> 34:59.257
Leather we found
with the victim’s tissue...

34:59.348 --> 35:01.009
inside a rat.

35:01.100 --> 35:03.261
If we can match this leather
to your shoes,

35:03.352 --> 35:05.638
it’ll show that you were there
when the victim died.

35:08.607 --> 35:11.519
You please remove
your shoes, Officer Grant?

35:19.660 --> 35:21.946
[ Exhales ]

35:22.037 --> 35:24.449
Eddie was a good guy.

35:24.540 --> 35:26.997
I just wanted
a little romance,

35:27.084 --> 35:29.040
but those letters
were a lie.

35:30.087 --> 35:32.703
I should have been happy
with Eddie.

35:32.798 --> 35:34.959
Should have been happy
with what I had.

35:50.190 --> 35:52.101
Thank you very much.

35:52.192 --> 35:54.319
I have a big article to write.

35:54.403 --> 35:56.769
Well, I hope you’ll stress
the important things
in my novels.

35:56.864 --> 35:59.321
I have learned very much.

35:59.408 --> 36:02.320
Yes. You learned
that rat excrement...

36:02.411 --> 36:04.527
can provide
not only a timeline,

36:04.621 --> 36:08.534
but also very important
non-circumstantial evidence.

36:08.625 --> 36:13.494
I also learned that
people should not take credit
for what other people write.

36:13.630 --> 36:17.919
What is that supposed to mean?
Uh, I mean the man
who was murdered, of course.

36:18.010 --> 36:20.046
Oh.

36:20.137 --> 36:23.755
[ Both Speaking Japanese]

36:36.779 --> 36:40.021
“Unseen, | feel your spirit
as we work.

36:40.115 --> 36:42.197
“The scent of your hair.

36:42.284 --> 36:45.151
“The accidental brush
of your skin.

36:45.245 --> 36:48.203
“I hear your heart beating,
mine beating with yours
as one.

36:48.290 --> 36:50.781
“I breathe when you breathe.

36:50.876 --> 36:53.663
Breath to breath,
heartbeat to heartbeat.”

36:53.796 --> 36:56.378
You believe Martin
wrote these letters to me?
Yeah.

36:56.465 --> 36:59.582
The imagery.
You know, the syntax,
the emotion.

36:59.676 --> 37:03.043
- Yes I do.
- So you’re saying
he was in love with me?

37:03.138 --> 37:06.050
I wasn’t sure
whether to tell you,

37:06.141 --> 37:09.633
but I figured
that if I was him,

37:09.728 --> 37:12.515
I wouldn’t want my fear
to prevent you
from knowing how I felt.

37:12.606 --> 37:14.517
But he never said anything.

37:14.608 --> 37:17.099
But Martin wouldn’t, would he?

37:19.196 --> 37:21.653
I was married.
I had children.

37:21.740 --> 37:23.696
l was happy.

37:24.785 --> 37:26.776
He could never have
what he wanted.

37:28.330 --> 37:30.286
Poor Martin.

37:38.507 --> 37:41.044
- What is this?
- It’s your share.

37:41.176 --> 37:43.087
My share of what?
My advance,

37:43.178 --> 37:45.669
plus an estimation
of what you deserve
for the other two books.

37:45.764 --> 37:49.803
Okay. Would you stop
talking as though I know
what you’re talking about?

37:49.893 --> 37:51.929
I’ve come to realize
over the past couple days...

37:52.020 --> 37:55.729
that you deserve 25%
of what I get from my books.

37:55.816 --> 37:57.727
Does this have to do
with Hodgins...

37:57.818 --> 38:00.525
and the whole sex thing
on page 187?

38:00.612 --> 38:02.603
Among other things.

38:02.698 --> 38:04.939
- So is this Booth’s idea?
- [ Stammers ] Oh, no.

38:05.033 --> 38:07.445
Uh, I did my own math.
Booth is terrible at math.

38:07.536 --> 38:10.528
Well, I meant
the whole “share” thing.

38:10.622 --> 38:12.533
Booth’s surprise
at your involvement...

38:12.624 --> 38:15.411
caused me to reevaluate
our arrangement.

38:18.213 --> 38:20.169
Oh!

38:21.216 --> 38:24.549
ls my math incorrect?
Wow! Um—

38:25.596 --> 38:28.508
This is— This is 25%?

38:28.599 --> 38:33.138
Yes. I figure
if my agent gets 10%,

38:33.228 --> 38:35.560
you deserve more.

38:45.365 --> 38:47.401
[Sweets]
Daisy?

38:47.493 --> 38:49.700
Lancelot.
There you are.
Don’t touch the bones.

38:49.786 --> 38:52.823
Oh, did it look like
I was going to?
I wasn’t.

38:52.915 --> 38:54.997
I’ve been trying
to call you.

38:55.083 --> 38:56.994
You’ve been avoiding me,
haven’t you?

38:57.085 --> 39:02.079
Yeah. I, uh— I just—
I needed to think
about some things.

39:05.594 --> 39:08.176
About you and-and me
and-and, uh,

39:08.263 --> 39:10.424
what I want my life to be.

39:14.937 --> 39:17.519
Is this because of the boy
who didn’t die of leukemia?

39:17.606 --> 39:20.222
Yeah.

39:20.317 --> 39:24.686
And you’re here because
you decided something.

39:24.780 --> 39:26.611
Yeah.

39:28.700 --> 39:31.077
Am I gonna like what you decided?

39:32.120 --> 39:34.611
I don’t know.

39:37.000 --> 39:39.116
I... just wanna say that,

39:39.211 --> 39:42.044
I don’t wanna spend
any more time away from you...

39:42.172 --> 39:45.835
than I have to.
What?

39:45.926 --> 39:47.837
I’m doin’ this wrong. Um—

39:48.929 --> 39:51.545
When my mom died,
she left me something,

39:51.640 --> 39:55.508
and my mom and dad were together
for almost 60 years.

39:55.644 --> 39:59.136
They were really old.
Yeah. They were really old
when they adopted me. Um—

40:00.190 --> 40:03.774
[ Sighs ]
It’s just a modest ring.

40:03.860 --> 40:06.647
It represents 60 years of love.

40:11.410 --> 40:15.198
Daisy, will you be my wife?

40:24.214 --> 40:27.832
It would make me
incredibly happy if
you would be my husband.

40:33.974 --> 40:36.090
l’m sorry
about everyone else—

40:36.184 --> 40:38.470
all the bad things.

40:38.562 --> 40:42.601
That earthquake
was the luckiest thing
in the world for me.

40:52.200 --> 40:54.236
[Knocking]

40:55.370 --> 40:57.361
You are not going
to believe this.

40:57.456 --> 40:59.617
Come in.
You want a drink?

40:59.750 --> 41:04.084
l have some Chinese food
in the refrigerator.
Uh, a drink. Scotch.

41:04.171 --> 41:06.662
What am | not gonna believe?

41:06.757 --> 41:08.543
Officer Grant got a lawyer.

41:08.634 --> 41:11.592
Well, we just
arrested her for murder.

41:11.720 --> 41:13.631
I believe that.
Right, but Eddie—

41:13.722 --> 41:16.304
Eddie got her the best
defense attorney in town.

41:16.433 --> 41:18.799
That is hard to believe.
I know, right?

41:18.894 --> 41:21.681
He heard what she did for him,
and he fell in love
with her all over again.

41:21.813 --> 41:23.314
That is not rational.
You know what?

41:23.398 --> 41:26.356
I still can be surprised
by people.

41:26.485 --> 41:29.693
Is that good or bad?
Uh, bad.

41:31.239 --> 41:33.446
I think.
[Sharp Inhale]
Wow.

41:33.533 --> 41:35.910
Um, I don’t know.

41:35.994 --> 41:38.326
Well, if she’s convicted,
even with good behavior...

41:38.413 --> 41:40.870
she’ll be in prison
for the next 15 years.

41:40.957 --> 41:42.868
Yeah, but he said
that they’re soul mates,

41:42.959 --> 41:45.416
and he’ll wait for however long
it takes for her to get out.

41:45.545 --> 41:47.126
Soul mates?
Soul mates.

41:47.255 --> 41:50.463
Yeah.
The idea of soul mates
actually originated with Plato.

41:50.550 --> 41:52.836
Yeah. You mean the—
the clay that kids play with?

41:52.928 --> 41:55.010
No. The a— Oh.

41:55.138 --> 41:56.218
[Laughs]
What?

41:56.348 --> 41:58.259
You’re joking.
Me joke? No.

41:58.350 --> 42:00.841
No, the ancient
Greek philosopher.

42:00.936 --> 42:03.678
His theory was that humans
originally consisted...

42:03.772 --> 42:06.730
of four arms, four legs
and two faces.

42:06.858 --> 42:09.941
Hmm.
Zeus was threatened
by their power,

42:10.028 --> 42:12.565
and split them all in half,
condemning us all...

42:12.656 --> 42:18.276
to spend our lives trying
to complete ourselves.

42:19.329 --> 42:21.866
I don’t believe that’s true.
[ Chuckles ]

42:21.957 --> 42:24.414
I agree. It’s ridiculous.

42:24.501 --> 42:27.163
Right?

42:28.255 --> 42:31.839
Four arms, four heads?

42:31.967 --> 42:35.130
Two faces.
Come on.

